nodes.title: Info
widgets_values:
=================================
 JPS Everything All At Once v1.0
=================================


Important
=========

It's highly recommended to change the "Link Render Mode" in ComfyUI to "Hidden" for a better user experience without annoying wires. That makes the menu area much more pleasant to look at.

Don't forget that you can zoom your workflow with your mouse wheel and also drag the workflow anywhere (not just on empty spaces) by holding the middle mouse button (in many cases the mouse wheel). Dragging the workflow that way is crucial, if you want to use the menu area on smaller screens.

You will need to change some nodes (models, images) to your own file names when using this workflow for the first time.

You can use keyboard shortcuts "1" to "4" to jump to different settings of the workflow.


Turn off Features
=================

It's recommended to use the toggles in the "Turn off functions" node to disable functions you don't intend to use at the moment. 

By doing this, you will save resources and avoid wasting time on parts of the workflow that aren't needed. The way ComfyUI works at the moment, every part of the workflow will be executed at least once, and in many cases every time, even if the current settings do not require that part of the workflow. The toggles under "Turn off functions" actually mute the nodes to prevent this.

If you want to fine-tune offset values (for source images), you can turn off "Standard Image (1x)" to quickly test many different offset values without waiting for the workflow to finish a full image generation.

I'd recommend turning off "Upscaled Image (2x)" and only turning it on when you like a standard resolution result. Just use the "Recycle Seed" button to recreate the same image again after turning it on.


Generation Settings (blue nodes)
================================

Only one IMG2IMG technique can be used at the same time. 

If you activate multiple methods you may waste resources and they will be used in the following order:

1. Inpainting (Model Conditioning)
2. Inpainting (Encode for Inpainting)
3. Unsampler
4. Image to Image

Only the applicable settings will be used. 

For best results, input images are resized to fit the output image or mode. If cropping is required, you can specify which part of the image you want to keep (center, top, bottom, left, right). The offset values allow you to fine-tune the cropping area. Use the preview images to verify your offset values.


Inpainting (see Generation Settings):
=====================================

To use inpainting, select "Open Mask Editor" from the context menu of "Generation Source Image". 

Two different Inpainting methods are available. Only one method will work at the same time.

Strength setting only works for "Inpainting (Model Conditioning)".

Grow Mask setting only works for "Inpainting (Encode for Inpainting)".


Unsampler (see Generation Settings):
====================================

Unsampler is an alternative to classic "Image to Image" and allows more fine-tuning and gives better results in many cases.


IP Adapter (yellow nodes)
=========================

Use images instead of or in addition to text prompts. You can merge images if you use more than one source image. 

Source images may be used in any number and order. If you don't want to use the feature, just turn off all IPA source images. Detailed options are only active when the corresponding IPA toggle is enabled - there is no need to manually reset each value to the default values when you disable a specific source image.

If you use more than one source image, they are processed in a chain - only this approach allows you to use different weights and noise values per source image, providing much more freedom of use than the batch processing advertised by the node's author. 

From my experience and testing, the overall quality is the same - in fact, in many cases I've gotten quite similar results when comparing the two approaches, as long as I've worked with appropriately adjusted weights. Please note that with this processing method the weight values are added up, which means while adding more source images you should also reduce the individual weights at the same time, so that the total sum is equal to the desired value again.

The source images will be cropped to a square aspect ratio as required by the Clip Vision model - this would be done internally anyway, but preparing the images allows you to influence the process and choose which part of the images to crop (center, top, bottom, left, right). The offset value allows you to fine-tune the area of cropping.

In addition, all source images are resized to the same size. You can choose between 224x224 (the resolution used internally by Clip Vision) or a higher resolution, and select different interpolation methods for resizing. Different settings can change the results - find the optimal values for the style and content you want to create.

For best results, keep the output size close to a square aspect ratio. "Extreme ratios" such as 16:9 or 21:9 do not work well and may require several attempts. You can try to combine IP Adapter with ControlNet to get better results for those ratios.

You may use the mask feature to control what part of the image is affected by that IP Adapter. Select "Open Mask Editor" from the context menu to create the mask. Try to use two IP Adapters for different sections (e.g. left/right or top/bottom) to get interesting results. You can use "Copy (Clipspace)" and "Paste (Clipspace)" to copy a previous result to the mask node for easier adjustment of the masks or copy the mask to another IP adapter and invert it. The image in the mask node will be ignored - only the mask is used. 

If you want to use RGB-masks you have to provide an image that uses RGB colors - use that image for multiple IP adapters and choose one IP Adapter per color.


Prompt Styler (work in progress)
================================

Select an artist, movie, or general style, and the text prompt will be expanded with appropriate keywords and phrases to produce images in that style.

You can also enable a "general negative prompt" which should have little to no effect on the style of the output image and will be suitable for many different images.


Resolution from settings or input image
=======================================

You can switch between using your own resolution/aspect ratio and using the aspect ratio of the input image. 

When you use the aspect ratio of the input image, the size is always adjusted to the closest recommended SDXL resolution.


Refiner
=======

If you don't want to use the refiner, just set "base_percentage" to 100.


Clip Skip
=========

The default value for Clip Skip is "-2". This will give you the same result as if you bypassed the Clip Skip node, while using the value "-1" will give you a different result.


Required nodes, models and other files
======================================

All required nodes are available through ComfyUI Manager:

* Mikey Nodes (for save and prompt)
* rgthree's ComfyUi Nodes (for output switch and better seed control)
* ComfyUI_IPAdapter_plus (for IP-Adapter)
* ComfyUI's ControlNet Auxiliary Preprocessors (for Control Net)
* ComfyUI_Noise (for Unsampler)
* JPS Custom Nodes for ComfyUI
